# Using variabel in Strings:
# In some situtation, you'll want to use a variable's value inside a string.

first_name = "ada"
last_name = "lovelace"
full_name = f"{first_name} {last_name}"
print(full_name)

print(f"Hello, {full_name.title()}!")
"""These full name is used in a sentece that greets the uer, and the
   title() method changes the name to title case. This code returns a simple
   but nicely formatted greeting:
"""
# You can also use f-strings to compose a message, and then assign the entire
# message to a variable:
message = f"Hello, {full_name.title()}!"
print(message)

full_name = "{} {}".format(first_name, last_name)
print(full_name.title())

# Adding Whitespace to Strings With Tabs or Newlines
"""
>>> print("Python")
Python
>>> print("\tPython")
        Python
>>> #to add a new line in a string, use the character combination \n:
>>> print("Languages: \nPython\nC\nJavaScript")
Languages:
Python
C
JavaScript

>>> Newlines and tabs will be very useful in the next two chapters when you
    start to produce many line of output from just a few lines of code.
"""

# Striping Whitspace:-
"""
>>> favorite_language = 'Python '
>>> favorite_language
'Python '
>>> favorite_language.rstrip()
'Python'
>>> favorite_language
'Python '

T0 insure that no whitespace exists at the right end of a string, use the
rstrip() method.
"""
"""
>>> favorite_language = 'Python '
>>> favorite_language = favorite_language.rstrip()
>>> favorite_language
'Python'
>>> favorite_language = ' python '
>>> favorite_language.rstrip()
' python'
>>> favorite_language.lstrip()
'python '
>>> favorite_language.strip()
'python'

When you use lstrip() to remove whitespace from left side
When you use rstrip() to remove whitespace from right side
When you use strip() to remove whitespace from both side
"""
